{{Multiple issues| {{notability|Organizations|date=June 2016}} {{refimprove|date=November 2014}} }}
{{Infobox Organization |name = Restore the Fourth |image = Restore the Fourth Logo.png |image_border = |alt = |size = |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = RT4 |motto = |formation = June 8, 2013, United States (incorporated 2014) |extinction = |type = 501(c)(4) nonprofit corporation |status = |purpose = Enforcement of Fourth Amendment rights |headquarters = Belmont, MA |location = |region_served = United States |membership = |language = |leader_title = National Chair |leader_name = Alex Marthews |main_organ = Board of Directors |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = {{Official website|http://www.restorethe4th.com/}} |remarks = }} '''Restore the Fourth''' is an American 501(c)(4) nonprofit that seeks to strengthen the [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] and end programs that violate it.<ref>{{cite web|title=Restore The Fourth FAQ|url=http://restorethe4th.com/faq/|accessdate=2014-06-04|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140604145757/http://restorethe4th.com/faq/|archivedate=2014-06-04|df=}}</ref><ref name=HuffPost1>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/28/restore-the-fourth_n_3519600.html/|title= Restore The Fourth: Group Organizes Nationwide Anti-NSA Spying Protests On July 4|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=2013-06-28}}</ref> It organized protests in 2013 and 2014, and in 2015 helped to introduce the Surveillance State Repeal Act, besides other lobbying activities.
==History== <gallery> File:NYC Restore The Fourth July 4th.jpg|Restore the Fourth NYC </gallery> Restore the Fourth originated on the [[social media]] website [[reddit]] shortly after the information leak by [[Edward Snowden]], which detailed the US [[National Security Agency]]'s (NSA) [[mass surveillance]] programs, most notably the [[PRISM (surveillance program)|PRISM]]. A subforum (known on reddit as a ''subreddit'') dedicated to the movement was created on June 8, 2013, garnering over 15,000 subscribers in 2 weeks.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} From there, Restore the Fourth moved to Snoonet, an [[IRC]] network for reddit communities. Most organization prior to July 4, 2013 occurred there, where local organizers, national organizers, and users from the subreddit collaborated.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}
The first Restore the Fourth protest occurred on June 30, 2013, in [[Madison, Wisconsin]]. Subsequent [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]] protests occurred on July 4 with more than 70 local rallies across all 50 [[U.S. state]]s and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=":0">[http://www.restorethefourth.net/protests/ Restore the Fourth Protests]</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/04/restore-the-fourth-protesters-nsa-surveillance|title=NSA surveillance: protesters stage Restore the Fourth rallies across US|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2013-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2013/07/04/crowds-across-america-protest-nsa-in-restore-fourth-movement/|title=Crowds across America protest NSA in 'Restore the Fourth' movement|work=[[Fox News]]|date=2013-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/04/tech/web/restore-nsa-protests/|title=Protests against the NSA spring up across U.S.|work=[[CNN]]|date=2013-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://swampland.time.com/2013/07/03/fourth-of-july-pro-snowden-rallies-coming-to-a-city-near-you/|title=Fourth of July Anti-NSA-Snooping Rallies Coming to a City Near You|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time magazine]]|date=2013-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/04/net-us-usa-security-internet-protest-idUSBRE9630O620130704|title=Internet sites join July 4 protest against surveillance|work=[[Reuters]]|date=2013-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-fi-tn-restore-the-fourth-nsa-july-4-20130703,0,228523.story|title=Protests against secret NSA tactics to light up Web July 4|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=2013-07-04}}</ref> On July 4, many protests hosted hundreds of attendees, and as many as 500 protesters attended the rallies in Washington, D.C. and 950 in [[New York City]].<ref name=":1" /> In Munich, Germany, protesters gathered in front of the U.S. Consulate wearing Edward Snowden masks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/04/tech/web/restore-nsa-protests/|title=Protests against the NSA spring up across U.S.|work=[[CNN]]|date=2013-07-04}}</ref> Organizers estimated a national turnout of more than 10,000.<ref name=":1">{{cite news|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/07/04/19287215-independence-day-nsa-leaks-inspire-fourth-amendment-rallies|title=Independence Day, NSA leaks inspire 'Fourth Amendment' rallies|work=[[NBC News]]|date=2013-07-04}}</ref>
Further rallies were held to mark Orwell Day (August 4), to push for the passage of the [[USA Freedom Act]] (October 26), and to call for the shutting down of the growing network of [[fusion centers]] across the United States (April 10).{{citation needed|date=November 2014}} During November 2013 - April 2014, the organization saw a period of significant turnover, before relaunching with national elections in May 2014 as a 501(c)(4) nonprofit with 25 chapters around the country, under the leadership of Alex Marthews.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}
==Stated goals== According to Restore The Fourth's legislative platform, the organization seeks to:
*Restore reliance on warrants based on individualized probable cause. *Impose penalties on agencies and agents who conduct surveillance not meeting this standard. *Pass legislation limiting the [[Third-Party Doctrine]], improving government transparency, and preventing end-runs around the Fourth Amendment by using foreign partner agencies or contractors.
==Responses== Restore the Fourth has received support from the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2013/07/restore-fourth-campaign-organizes-protests-against-unconstitutional-surveillance|title=Restore the Fourth Campaign Organizes Protests Against Unconstitutional Surveillance|work=[[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]|date=2013-07-01}}</ref> Sen. [[Rand Paul]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://swampland.time.com/2013/07/03/fourth-of-july-pro-snowden-rallies-coming-to-a-city-near-you/|title=Fourth of July Anti-NSA-Snooping Rallies Coming to a City Near You|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Nicole|last=Greenstein|date=July 3, 2013}}</ref> and Judge [[Andrew Napolitano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://original.antiwar.com/andrew-p-napolitano/2015/05/06/restore-the-fourth/|title=Restore the Fourth|work=[[Antiwar.com]]|date=2015-05-07}}</ref>
The NSA addressed the July 4 protest in a statement, saying: "The Fourth of July reminds us as Americans of the freedoms and rights all citizens of our country are guaranteed by our Constitution. Among those is freedom of speech, often exercised in protests of various kinds. NSA does not object to any lawful, peaceful protest."<ref name=":1"/>
